      <body>
         <div type="transcription">
            <p>
<lb corresp="#a1"/><w>k<supplied>a</supplied>vāre</w><w>oki</w>
<lb corresp="#a2"/><w>kātkāśi</w></p>
         </div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#a1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">like morsels</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">of the householders</seg></seg></choice></p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p><note corresp="#a1" type="lingcomment">The interpretation of this gloss is uncertain: the reading is not secured and the Sanskrit text is incomplete. If the gloss is read correctly, <hi>k(a)vāre</hi> may stand for <hi>kāpāre</hi> 'morsels, bite-size pieces' (<bibl><title corresp="ref:carlingetal2009"/><citedRange>113a</citedRange></bibl>). Since <hi>kāpār</hi> is borrowed from (a Middle Indian form corresponding to) Skt. <hi>kavaḍa</hi> (see Carling, l.c.), it is understandable that the word was spelled differently. Both the short <hi>a</hi> and the <hi>v</hi> are closer to the Skt. form. The semantic connection may be understood as 'crushed' = 'small pieces'. Even if Waldschmidt's cautious restoration to <hi>(na)[ṭa]kuṭṭā</hi> 'wie Spaßmacher' ['like jesters'] (in <bibl><title corresp="ref:sanderandwaldschmidt1985"/><citedRange>89</citedRange></bibl>) is correct, the TA gloss could be an “incorrect” too literal rendering of only the last part of the word.</note><note corresp="#a1" type="philcomment">glosses Skt. /// <hi>[ṭ]·kuṭṭā</hi> 'crushing, bruising...'</note><note corresp="#a2" type="lingcomment">Pace <bibl><title corresp="ref:malzahn2007b"/><citedRange>305</citedRange></bibl> (accepted by <bibl><title corresp="ref:carlingetal2009"/><citedRange>111b-112</citedRange></bibl>a), who sees a connection with <hi>kātk-</hi> 'be glad', <hi>kātkāśi</hi> does not gloss the following word <hi>hāsyaprekṣy</hi> 'makes laugh'. Apart from the fact that the gloss is actually found under <hi>gṛhiṇo</hi>, <hi>kātkāśi</hi> could not possibly be a form of <hi>kātk-</hi>: there is no agent suffix <hi>-śi</hi> v.s., and probably no stem of a causative of this structure would have a long <hi>ā</hi> in the second syllable, not even the subjunctive stem (<bibl><title corresp="ref:malzahn2010"/><citedRange>216-7</citedRange></bibl>, <bibl><title corresp="ref:peyrot2013b"/><citedRange>128-9</citedRange></bibl>). TA <hi>kātkāśi</hi>, for <hi>kātkāśśi</hi>, is probably in th eplural because this word has become a plurale tantum: no singular forms are attested at all and the nom.sg. <hi>kātak*</hi> (<bibl><title corresp="ref:carlingetal2009"/><citedRange>110b</citedRange></bibl>) is set up on the basis of plural forms.</note><note corresp="#a2" type="philcomment">glosses Skt. <hi>gṛhiṇo</hi> (gen.sg.) 'householder'. To the right of <hi>kātkāśi</hi> a further gloss <hi>hā</hi> is found, which clarifies that the first akṣara of <hi>hāsyaprekṣy</hi> is to be read <hi>hā</hi>: this akṣara is difficult to read and seems to have been corrected from <hi>p</hi>.</note></p>
         </div>
